         <abstract>
            <p>The efficient markets hypothesis implies that any attempt to gain investment advantage by such analysis is an exercise in futility. Defending fundamental investment analysis against the hypothesis, the author argues that: (1) In any creative field only a few reap unusual rewards; (2) even if information propagates very rapidly, these few investors may still be able to profit from superior interpretation; and (3) although fundamental analysis may have limited usefulness in forecasting price/earnings ratios, it can still be useful in forecasting earnings.</p>
          </abstract>
